metadata.name: Ceremony #322
metadata.description:
This series celebrates fxhash turning one. #fxhashturnsone

Iâ€™m so grateful for this place and have ho idea how to adequately articulate how much this platform has changed my life, but it has. A million thanks to the team. You are so appreciated as are the artists and collectors that have made this such a beautiful community. ðŸ¥‚

Definitely check out â€œForeverâ€ mode by tapping â€œFâ€ or mouse click/tap â€” it will animate (you guessed it) forever and will change its layout every 365 frames, in honor of this wonderful year, and every year after. Some forever modes will â€œnever forgetâ€ and others will fade as they progress. No idea if thatâ€™s a metaphor but it is a trait, that much I know.

All primary sales are donated to Code/Art, which is a charity that uses â€œâ€¦Art to Inspire Girls in Computer Science.â€ Read about Code/Art here: https://www.code-art.com/

Ceremony uses public domain art (which is the original, more implicit version CC0) made exclusively by women.

See fxtext article linked from the project page for a gallery of the source material and other notes.

Ceremony is also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

F : â€œForeverâ€ mode (tap after initial render completes)
P : Pause/Play
(mouse click/tap also works to start â€œForeverâ€ mode or Pause/Play)

metadata.name: Ichigo #344
metadata.description:
This generator is named 'Ichigo' (è‹º/ ã„ã¡ã”), the Japanese word for 'strawberry'. 

Seeing each iteration from a suitable distance, small dots (to me, reminiscent of strawberry seeds) overlay different sequences of geometric repetitions, implying a sense of texture, grittiness and irregularity. 

By looking closer however, it becomes apparent to the viewer that the majority of the composition is in fact government by orderly elements, in this case grids of dots. 

This discovery invites the viewer to consider the output in front of them at different levels, near and far. At what point do you feel the dots begin to dissolve into a texture? When do you stop noticing the dots and instead begin to perceive the overall composition?

These questions are posed in a similar fashion as with meditation; at what point does something become something else? When does an in-breath become an out-breath and vice versa? 

Contemplation on simple questions like these can open a small portal into stillness and mindfulness by taking time to slowly observe our responses. 

23 palettes are included, each named after different areas of Tokyo. 

Press 'S' to download a full size 6000px x 6000px PNG output. 

As always, much gratitude and enjoy your piece.

metadata.name: Coronado #53
metadata.description:
This series is about the beauty and charm of imperfection, chaos amidst order, and letting go. It's about knowing that however much control we think we may have, things can all fall apart or burst into something unexpectedly wonderful at any moment, even without our hands tightly on the reigns.

Please see fxtext article linked from main project page for more background on the project and rendering notes.

Some key commands in live mode:

G : Toggle grain
S : Save current resolution
1 : 4000x5000
2 : 6000x7500
3 : 8000x10000
4 : 10000x12500
5 : 12000x15000
6 : 14000x17500
(1-6 work best on Chrome)
(rendering takes longer as resolution increases)

metadata.name: WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition #392
metadata.description:
WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition is our official collaboration with Jeres, who was kind enough to work with us in support of the show. The project leans into classic Olympic poster design motifs, embellished by Jeres' signature approach to color and shape. Huge thanks to Jeres for donating their time and enthusiasm to this one, we hope you enjoy it!

As with all WTBS projects, your minting will directly support the podcast and keep us going (and more importantly, collecting!). Our goal is to keep the show free from ads and fully supported by the community, your donations and contributions continue to make that possible. Thank you in advance to everyone who chooses to mint!

Jeres: I love vintage posters. When going to second-hand shops, flea markets or wherever people are selling their used goods, Iâ€™m always on the lookout for what people used to hang on their walls. Bauhaus-inspired posters, socialist propaganda, Nagel prints, anything art deco, etc.. but whenever I come across something Olympics inspired I always feel like I hit pay dirt. Thereâ€™s something about the clean, simple design being used to show people coming together along with the undertones of human excellence that just feels special. And circles. I love circles. I hope you enjoy this collection as much as I enjoyed putting it together with Trinity and Will.

Approximate rarity notes:
5%: Gold Edition
10%: Silver Edition
15%: Bronze Edition 

Commands in fullscreen mode:
S : Save current resolution
1 : Save 2000x3000px
2 : Save 4000x6000px
3 : Save 6000x9000px
4 : Save 8000x12000px
5 : Save 10000x15000px

(The higher the resolution, the longer it takes to render/save. use Chrome for best results.)

metadata.name: E s q u a d r o s #28
metadata.description:
Set-square is an instrument in the form of a right triangle, used to draw angles and perpendiculars, in Portuguese we call it Esquadro.

When developing this study, I reflected on the action of order and disorder of alignments, the need I feel when instinctively seeking order and at the same time learning to live with disorder. Programming was like learning to draw all over again, and in Esquadros I try to extrapolate this issue by using simple geometric shapes and slightly playful colors, portraying this phase of starting over.

Esquadros displays some simple variations: density, palettes, a little clutter in some pieces and some inverted colors.

Appreciate the simple shapes and colors that life offers us, even in the midst of a lot of order and disorder. This is my genesis for Fx Hash.

Key controls:

k : save png
l : show pallete label

Artwork by Zizou, @Zizoutez.

Made with p5.js and <3

metadata.name: Chroma-Sphere #63
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender renders.

The prefix 'Chroma' refers to the large color palette used in the Chroma series.

Each 'Chroma-Sphere' is in fact a partial Geodesic dome, made up of 5 equilateral triangles and 15 isosceles triangles. Coupled with the carefully balanced colors, each output forms a bold, striking 'spherical' design.

In live mode:
Click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 2000x2000px PNG.
